=== Surveillance_Concerns ===
Digital ID and the Online Safety Act together create a blueprint for mass surveillance. # diagram: surveillance_blueprint.png

Even if implemented in good faith by this government, the infrastructure persists.
A future UK government could use these systems to track both online and offline activity.

Consider what becomes possible:

Simply having a digital ID app installed can allow silent, real-time tracking to your physical location. # diagram: location_tracking.png

Protests. Medical appointments. Religious services. Union meetings.
Your phone becomes a tracking beacon that can be queried without a warrant.

Browsing history can be tied to your real identity without judicial oversight. # diagram: browsing_surveillance.png

Every website you visit.
Every article you read.
Every video you watch.
All linked to your name, address, and face.

Face scans gathered for digital ID registration or age-verification produce high-quality biometric data suitable for facial recognition. # diagram: facial_recognition.png

The data collected is far more than what's claimed.
Age-verification companies are already collecting more data than they admit to.

Once this infrastructure exists, the temptation to use it grows with every crisis.

*   [That sounds dystopian.]
    It does. But it's not hypothetical—the framework is being built right now.
    And unlike temporary emergency powers, this infrastructure is permanent.
